-- Russia 5-year CDS rise to 3-week high
-- 
-- Mon Apr 14, 2014 04:17AM EDT
-- None



LONDON, April 14 (Reuters) - Russia's default insurance costs rose on Monday and sovereign dollar bonds fell as renewed tensions in Ukraine weighed on Russian assets.

After weeks of calm, Ukraine and Russia were again under investors' focus as fears grew for military action in eastern Ukraine where pro-Russian separatists have been occuping state buildings [ID:nL6N0N614A]. Russia 5-year credit default swaps rose 17 basis points from Friday's close to a 3-week high of 240 bps, according to Markit. Russia's 2023 sovereign dollar bond fell 1.7 cents to 97.042 <RU097172145=>.